ic dividing lines are blurred and transcended, but also fortified and redrawn. This volume notably places right-wing and social justice initiatives in the same analytical frame to identify patterns that span the political spectrum. Border Politics offers a lens through which to understand borders as sites of diverse struggles, as well as the strategies and practices used by diverse social movements in today's globally interconnected world. Contributors: Phillip Ayoub, Renata Blumberg, Yvonne Braun, Moon Charania, Michael Dreiling, Jennifer Johnson, Jesse Klein, Andrej Kurnik, Sarah Maddison, Duncan McDuie-Ra, Jennifer Bickham Mendez, Nancy A. Naples, David Paternotte, Maple Razsa, Raphi Rechitsky, Kyle Rogers, Deana Rohlinger, Cristina Sanidad, Meera Sehgal, Tara Stamm, Michelle Tellez"--cProvided by publisher.  a16 29 0aBoundariesxSocial aspects. 0aBorderlandsxSocial aspects. 0aGroup identity. 0aCollective memory. 0aSocial movements.1 aNaples, Nancy A.1 aMéndez, Jennifer Bickham.423Cover imageuhttp://www.netread.com/jcusers/1313/2883701/image/lgcover.9781479898992.jpg  aJC 323 B648 2015c1hUAAU-Bi0162035236510  aJC 323 B648 2015wLCc1i0162035236510d7/4/2016e5/30/2016lON_SHELFmUAAUGn7p$150.00rYsYtBOOKu2/11/2015  aJC323 .B648 2015wLCc1i1007431669d2/25/2015lON_SHELFmGR_MACEWANp$33.75rYsYtBOOKu2/12/201501bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/15070506